Group A: Short Questions (2 Marks)
1. Differentiate between Legibility and Readability.
•	Legibility: How easily individual letters or characters can be recognized. Focuses on font, size, and spacing.
•	Readability: How easily words, sentences, and text can be understood. Focuses on writing style, structure, and content clarity.

2. What is the ”Rule of Thirds” in layout design?
The Rule of Thirds is a design principle that divides a layout into nine equal parts 
using two equally spaced horizontal lines and two equally spaced vertical lines.

Application:
	•	Important elements (like images, text, or buttons) are placed along these lines or at their intersections.
	•	This creates a balanced, visually appealing, and engaging layout.

Purpose:
	•	Guides the viewer’s eye naturally.
	•	Avoids placing elements in the center, which can feel static or uninteresting.

3. Why should you limit the number of font families used on a website?
Limiting Font Families on a Website:

Using too many font families can negatively impact a website because:
	1.	Consistency: Too many fonts make the design look cluttered and unprofessional.
	2.	Readability: Mixing multiple fonts can confuse users and reduce reading comfort.
	3.	Performance: Each font adds to page load time, slowing down the website.
	4.	Visual Hierarchy: Fewer fonts help maintain a clear hierarchy and emphasize important content.

Best Practice: Use 1–2 font families—one for headings and another for body text—to keep the site clean, readable, and visually appealing.

4. Define ”Responsive Web Design.”
Responsive Web Design is an approach to web design where a website automatically adjusts its layout, 
content, and elements to fit different screen sizes and devices (desktops, tablets, smartphones).

Purpose:
	•	Ensures optimal user experience across all devices.
	•	Eliminates the need for separate mobile and desktop sites.
	•	Improves accessibility, usability, and search engine rankings.


Group B: Long Questions (4 Marks)
5. Explain the ”F-Pattern” of scanning and how it influences the placement of content on a
web page.
F-Pattern of Scanning:

The F-Pattern is a common way users read and scan web pages, discovered through eye-tracking studies. Users tend to:
	1.	Scan horizontally across the top of the page (forming the top bar of the “F”).
	2.	Move slightly down and scan another horizontal line (forming the lower bar).
	3.	Scan the left side vertically to check headings, bullet points, or links (forming the vertical stem).

Influence on Content Placement:
	•	Place the most important content, headings, and calls-to-action along the top and left side.
	•	Use short paragraphs, bullet points, and highlighted keywords to match scanning behavior.
	•	Helps ensure critical information is seen quickly, improving user engagement and readability.


6. Discuss the psychological impact of colors in web design. Give examples of where Blue,
Red, and Green should be used.
Psychological Impact of Colors in Web Design:

Colors influence emotions, perception, and user behavior. Choosing the right color can enhance usability, engagement, and brand identity.

Examples:
	1.	Blue:
	•	Psychological Effect: Trust, calmness, professionalism.
	•	Usage: Banking websites, corporate sites, social media platforms (e.g., Facebook, LinkedIn).
	2.	Red:
	•	Psychological Effect: Excitement, urgency, attention-grabbing.
	•	Usage: Call-to-action buttons, sales, warnings, or promotional banners.
	3.	Green:
	•	Psychological Effect: Growth, safety, relaxation.
	•	Usage: Environmental sites, health and wellness, success messages, or “confirm” actions.

Conclusion:
Using colors strategically enhances user experience, guides attention, and reinforces brand messaging.


7. Explain the ”60-30-10 Rule” regarding color balance on a website.
60-30-10 Rule in Web Design:

The 60-30-10 Rule is a guideline for creating a balanced and visually appealing color scheme on a website:
	1.	60% - Dominant Color:
	•	Used for the main background or large areas.
	•	Sets the overall tone of the site.
	2.	30% - Secondary Color:
	•	Used for supporting elements like sidebars, menus, or panels.
	•	Adds contrast and visual interest without overwhelming the user.
	3.	10% - Accent Color:
	•	Used sparingly for highlights, buttons, links, or call-to-action elements.
	•	Draws attention to important content or actions.

Purpose:
	•	Ensures visual hierarchy.
	•	Prevents color overload.
	•	Enhances user focus and engagement.


Group C: Scenario-Based Questions (5 Marks) 
8.A website loads very slowly, causing users to abandon it. Upon inspection, you find the
developer used high-resolution raw images directly from a camera. Explain the importance
of Image Optimization and file formats (JPEG vs PNG) to solve this.
Issue: Slow website due to high-resolution raw images.

Importance of Image Optimization:
	•	Reduces file size without significantly affecting visual quality.
	•	Improves page load speed, enhancing user experience and SEO.
	•	Saves bandwidth and server resources.

File Formats:
	1.	JPEG:
	•	Best for photographs and images with many colors.
	•	Compressed format → smaller file size.
	•	Lossy compression may slightly reduce quality.
	2.	PNG:
	•	Best for images with transparency, logos, or graphics with sharp edges.
	•	Lossless compression → preserves quality but larger file size than JPEG.

Solution:
	•	Resize images to the required display dimensions.
	•	Compress them using JPEG for photos and PNG for graphics/logos.
	•	This reduces load time, improving usability and keeping users engaged.


9. You are designing a website for a Law Firm. The client wants to use a bright yellow
background with Comic Sans font to look ”friendly.” As a web designer, critique this choice
based on Color Theory and Typography principles, and suggest a better alternative.
Critique of the Client’s Choice:
	1.	Color Theory:
	•	Bright yellow is very intense and can strain the eyes when used as a background.
	•	Yellow conveys energy or caution, which may not align with the professional, trustworthy image expected for a law firm.
	2.	Typography:
	•	Comic Sans is informal and playful, giving a non-serious impression, which is inappropriate for a professional legal service.

Suggested Alternative:
	•	Background Color: Use neutral or muted tones such as white, light gray, or soft beige to convey professionalism and readability.
	•	Font Choice: Use serif fonts like Times New Roman, Georgia, or professional sans-serif fonts like Arial or Helvetica for a clean, 
authoritative look.

Result:
	•	Conveys trust, credibility, and professionalism.
	•	Enhances readability and creates a user-friendly, visually balanced website.


10. A website looks great on a laptop but is unreadable on a mobile phone because the user has
to zoom in and scroll horizontally. Identify the design principle missing here and explain
how Media Queries/Fluid Grids could fix it.
Missing Design Principle: Responsive Web Design (RWD)

Problem: The website is not adapting to different screen sizes, making it hard to read on mobile devices. 
Users must zoom and scroll horizontally, which hurts usability.

Solution Using Media Queries and Fluid Grids:
	1.	Media Queries:
	•	CSS rules that apply different styles based on device width, height, or orientation.
	•	Example: Adjust font sizes, hide or rearrange elements for mobile screens.
	2.	Fluid Grids:
	•	Layouts use percentage-based widths instead of fixed pixels, 
allowing content to resize dynamically across different screen sizes.

Result:
	•	The website automatically adapts to any device, providing a readable, user-friendly experience without horizontal scrolling or zooming.
